The Archbishop had, of course, heard of these outrages, and he did not wait for the formal report of his Commis- saries (which was dated, at Exeter, on the 4th of June), but pro- ceeded to deal with the offenders at once, issuing, on the 29th of April, his Mandate, directed to the Precentor and Canons of the Cathedral, “ad denunciandum excommunicatos impedientes execu- cioncm ipsius Mandati.'’ This was speedily followed by a Mandate to cite the Bishop himself, “viis et modis,” dated at Exeter on the ssth ; with what result the precentor certified, on the 2lst, as follows, ——“ Cujus auctoritate Mandati vestri reverendi, quia dictum Venerabilem Patrem, vel Procuratorem ejusdem, invenire non potui, absque dilacione quacumque ad Palacium in Civitate personaliter accessi, ad citandum eumdem juxta exigenciam Mandati vestri memo- ratr, ibique, coram Custode dicti Palacii ac aliis notis et familiaribus dlctl Patris, Mandatum vestrum, ut mandatur, publicavi, et in die proximo tunc sequenti, videlicet Festo Corporis Christi [which fell on the 9th of «June in 1384], in Ecclesia Cathedrali Exoniensi, in presencia Notarii Publici Ministrorumque ejusdem Ecclesie, ac alio- rum testium infrascriptorum, eumdem Venerabilem Patrem, Publice Citacioiris edicto per me publice proposito, ad comparendum coram v0b1s‚ dictis die et 1000, cum continuacione et prorogacione dierum
